  "opinion": "As a woman who's worked in the trades for over forty years as an electrician in Lecce, I've seen how stereotypes about who belongs in STEM fields can hold people back. Stereotype threat isn't just a theory—it's real. When students or colleagues from underrepresented groups hear that 'girls don't do math' or 'women aren't good at engineering,' it creates anxiety that can make them underperform. I remember when I first started, I was told by a supervisor that I 'shouldn't be here' because I was a woman. That comment stuck with me and made me question my abilities. But the truth is, stereotype threat is a barrier that needs to be addressed, not ignored. We need to start by changing how we talk about STEM in our communities. In my town, we have a few local workshops for kids, and I've noticed that when we focus on practical skills like fixing a broken circuit or building something useful, the kids—especially girls—get more engaged. The key is to make STEM feel accessible and relevant, not like something only for a select few. We should also encourage teachers and parents to talk about diversity in STEM without making it about 'fixing' people. It's about creating an environment where everyone feels they belong. I've seen this work in my own life—when I share my journey as a woman in the trades, it helps others see that they too can succeed. So yes, we should address stereotype threat in STEM. But the way we do it matters: by focusing on real-world applications, listening to those who've been affected, and making sure everyone feels valued from the start.",
